INTRODUCTION¶

In this analysis, we perform a detailed assessment of a supermarket sales dataset that we got from Kaggle. The dataset contains detailed information on product lines, payment methods, customer demographics, and sales transactions, with a total of 1000 entries and 17 columns. Our objective is to get relevant data and identify significant patterns that will support the store's strategic decision-making.

Our objectives are to detect patterns in customer behaviour, understand the effectiveness of different product categories, assess the usefulness of substitute payment methods, and look into how a customer's membership status affects sales through thorough data analysis. We will also examine factors like total revenue, peak transaction hours, and sales dispersion throughout different cities in order to provide a complete picture of the supermarket's operations.

With this study, we want to provide useful data that will, by directing marketing tactics, enhancing operational performance, and optimising inventory management, help the supermarket thrive in a competitive market.

Let's take a close look at the data to uncover any patterns that might help our business become more profitable and expand.

plt.ylabel('Quantity of Customers')

# Annotate each bar with the count value

    plt.text(index, value, str(value), ha='center', va='bottom')

# Display the plot
plt.show()

# Average Rating by Product Line
rating_by_product_line = supermarket.groupby('Product line')['Rating'].mean().reset_index()
sns.barplot(x='Rating', y='Product line', data=rating_by_product_line)
plt.title('Average Rating by Product Line')
plt.show()

# Sales Performance by Product Line
product_line_sales = supermarket.groupby('Product line')['Total'].sum().reset_index()
sns.barplot(x='Total', y='Product line', data=product_line_sales)
plt.title('Total Sales by Product Line')
plt.show()


#Gross Margin Analysis

plt.ylabel('Total Sales')

In [19]:
# Group data by City and Payment, summing up Total sales
sales_by_city_payment = supermarket.groupby(['City', 'Payment'])['Total'].sum().unstack(fill_value=0)

# Determine the number of cities for plotting
num_cities = len(sales_by_city_payment.index)

# Set the bar width and create an index for each city
bar_width = 0.27
index = np.arange(num_cities)

# Create the plot with a specified figure size
plt.figure(figsize=(13, 5), dpi=80)

# Plot bars for each payment method
for i, payment_method in enumerate(sales_by_city_payment.columns):
    plt.bar(index + bar_width * i, sales_by_city_payment[payment_method], bar_width, label=payment_method)

# Labeling the axes and setting up ticks and grid
plt.xlabel('City', fontsize=11)
plt.ylabel('Total Sales', fontsize=11)
plt.xticks(index + bar_width * (len(sales_by_city_payment.columns) / 2 - 0.3), sales_by_city_payment.index, fontsize=11, rotation=90)
plt.yticks(fontsize=11)
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--')

# Add legend to the plot
plt.legend(fontsize=12, loc='lower right')

# Add text annotations above each bar
for i, payment_method in enumerate(sales_by_city_payment.columns):
    for j, value in enumerate(sales_by_city_payment[payment_method]):
        plt.text(j + i * bar_width, value, str(round(value, 2)), ha='center', fontsize=10, verticalalignment='bottom')

# Adjust layout to prevent clipping of labels
plt.tight_layout()

# Display the plot
plt.show()

SUMMARY¶

Data Gathering and First Inspections: Data loading and library imports: The analysis starts with the import of many necessary libraries, such as seaborn, matplotlib.pyplot, pandas, and numpy. To load the dataset, use pd.read_csv(). Initial Data Examination: supermarket.info() is used to investigate data types, supermarket.head(10) is used to preview the first 10 rows, and the dataset is shown as part of basic data checks. Check for Missing Values: The analysis determines the proportion of missing data by using supermarket.isnull().sum() to evaluate the missing values in each column. The analysis continues as no meaningful missing data were discovered. Check for Duplicate Values: To make sure there are no duplicate entries, duplicate rows are enumerated and examined using supermarket.duplicated().

Graphics and Descriptive Statistics: Average Customer Rating: supermarket['Rating'].mean() is used to compute the average rating from all customers, and the result is reported. Gender Distribution: A countplot with seaborn is used to compute and display the number of consumers by gender. A bar chart that has been annotated for clarity shows the distribution of gender. Average Rating by Product Line: To illustrate performance across product categories, the average rating for each product line is pooled and displayed using a bar chart. Sales Performance: A bar chart is used to display the total sales by product line and shows which product lines bring in the most money. Analysis and Visualisation of Average Gross Margin Percentage by Product Line: This analysis and visualisation sheds light on the relative profitability of various product lines.

Analysis of Sales and Payments: Sales Distribution by Payment Method: A pie chart displays the sales distribution among various payment methods, indicating the preferred mode of payment for clients. Customer Demographics: To identify spending trends among various customer groupings, total sales are split down by gender and customer type and visualised using bar charts. Sales by Time of Day: To determine the busiest shopping hours, sales data is compiled each hour and plotted on a line. Sales Trend Over Time: To identify patterns over time, daily sales trends are examined by adding up all of the sales for each day. The trend is then plotted on a line plot.

Advanced Interpretation: Sales by Product Line and Gender: To determine which product lines perform better with different genders, a stacked bar chart illustrates the link between sales, gender, and product line. Sales vs. Gross Income: A scatter plot illustrates the correlation between sales and gross income, providing information on the link between sales volume and income. Product Sales Distribution: The distribution of product categories is shown in a bar chart, which also shows which product lines are most and least prevalent in the dataset. Sales by City and Payment Method: To better understand regional variations and payment preferences, a grouped bar chart displays total sales by city and payment method. Correlation Heatmap: A heatmap shows the numerical variables in the dataset correlated with one another, revealing possible connections and linkages.

The inquiry yields valuable insights into customer behaviour, product performance, and sales patterns. This information may be used to improve operational effectiveness, refine product offerings, and optimise marketing strategies.

RECOMMENDATIONS¶

Optimise Product Offerings: The information reveals that different product lines have different average ratings and sales results. While assessing and enhancing underperforming product lines, concentrate on marketing top-performing ones. This might entail making changes to inventory, improving marketing initiatives, or launching specials to increase sales of underperforming goods.

Customise Marketing Plans Based on Population: Different spending habits may be seen when sales are broken down by customer type and gender. Create specialised advertising campaigns by using these information. For example, if some product lines work better with particular client kinds or genders, make customised ads and promotions to better target these groups.

Utilise Sales Trends for Inventory Management: Sales data over time and by time of day reveal patterns in the purchase habits of customers. Make the most of workforce and inventory management by using this information. Achieve optimal customer service and well-stocked high-demand items by coordinating staff schedules and stock levels with peak shopping hours and seasonal patterns.
